Isoperimetric Efficiency as a
Pre-Simplification Diagnostic
for Area-Preserving Shape Approximation
 
Working Paper  |  March 2026

Abstract

We introduce the isoperimetric efficiency score E² = 4πA/P² as a compact geometric prior for predicting boundary information loss under equal-area shape simplification. Building on a universal invariant in the equal-area transform chain — the circle-to-square boundary ratio R_CS = 2/√π, which is constant for all regular n-gons — we propose E² as a pre-algorithm triage feature that classifies shape regions by expected simplification cost before any approximation algorithm is run. A synthetic study using COCO-taxonomy shape class distributions (N=500 per class) demonstrates strong negative correlation between E² and simplification error across all eight tested categories (r ranging from −0.43 to −0.84). We define a three-tier triage system (High/Medium/Low cost) aligned with shape class, and argue this gives simplification pipelines a theoretically grounded stopping criterion lacking in current empirical approaches. The framework requires no simulation, runs in O(1) per shape, and is domain-agnostic.
 
1. Introduction

Shape simplification algorithms — Ramer-Douglas-Peucker, visvalingam-Whyatt, and their variants — are widely deployed in geographic information systems, computer vision pipelines, and medical image analysis. These algorithms share a common limitation: they lack principled stopping criteria. The decision of when to stop simplifying is typically governed by empirical thresholds (epsilon values, point-count targets) that are set by domain convention rather than derived from the geometry of the shape being simplified.
This paper proposes that the isoperimetric quotient, reframed as a shape efficiency score E², provides exactly such a criterion. The core observation is geometric: under equal-area transform chains, the ratio of circle circumference to equal-area square perimeter is a universal constant independent of the starting polygon's side count. This invariant, R_CS = 2/√π ≈ 1.128, implies that the circle acts as a normalization lens — and that every shape's distance from the circle is precisely measurable via E².
We make the following contributions:
• A derivation of the universal transform chain invariant R_CS and its independence from n
• A reframing of E² as an isotropy efficiency prior for simplification pipelines
• A synthetic COCO-class study validating E² as a predictor of simplification error
• A three-tier triage system for pre-algorithm precision budget allocation
 
2. Mathematical Foundation

2.1 The Equal-Area Transform Chain
Let a regular n-gon have side length a. Its area and perimeter are:
A_n = (n·a²) / (4·tan(π/n))      P_n = n·a
The equal-area circle has radius r_n = √(A_n/π), giving circumference:
C_n = a · √(π·n / tan(π/n))
The equal-area square has side s_n = √(A_n), giving perimeter:
P□_n = 2a · √(n / tan(π/n))
2.2 The Three Boundary Ratios
We define three ratios capturing boundary distortion across the transform chain:
R_PC(n) = √(π / n·tan(π/n))          [Polygon → Circle]
R_CS     = 2/√π  ≈  1.1284            [Circle → Square, constant for all n]
R_PS(n) = 2 · √(1 / n·tan(π/n))      [Polygon → Square]
The key result is that R_CS is independent of n. This is not an approximation — it holds exactly for every regular polygon, triangle through circle. The proof follows directly from the area cancellation in C_n and P□_n, both proportional to √A_n.
2.3 The Shape Efficiency Score
We define the isoperimetric efficiency:
E = 2√(πA) / P      →      E² = 4πA / P²
E² equals 1 for a circle and is strictly less than 1 for all other shapes. For regular n-gons, E²_n = π / (n·tan(π/n)), which is exactly R_PC(n)². This quantity is equivalent to the isoperimetric quotient, known in the literature as the circularity index.
The novel interpretive move is treating E² as a proxy for angular suppression: the degree to which a shape's corners and edges prevent isotropic coupling between interior and boundary. Under this framing, R_CS = 2/√π is the conversion constant between maximum-isotropy boundary (circle) and minimum-isotropy rectilinear boundary (square), and π enters as the normalization constant for isotropic boundary efficiency in Euclidean 2-space.
 
