3. E² as a Pre-Simplification Diagnostic

3.1 The Diagnostic Hypothesis
When a shape is simplified to a target representation — whether a reduced-vertex polygon, bounding box, or rectilinear approximation — boundary information is lost. The quantity of boundary information is proportional to perimeter under fixed area. Shapes with lower E² have more perimeter relative to their area, meaning they encode more boundary structure, which is harder to preserve under simplification.
We therefore hypothesize: E² negatively predicts simplification error. Specifically, for a shape simplified to its equal-area rectilinear approximation, the boundary distortion is bounded below by a function of R_PS(n), where n is the effective polygon equivalence class of the shape (the n such that E²_n ≈ E²_shape).
This gives a pre-algorithm diagnostic: compute E² for each region mask, classify into triage tier, and allocate precision budget (vertex retention, simplification tolerance) proportionally.
3.2 Triage Classification
We define three triage zones based on the regular polygon reference values:
• High cost zone: E² < 0.65 (below square reference). Shapes in this range are organically irregular — animals, biological contours, complex food shapes. They lose the most information under simplification and require the tightest tolerances.
• Medium cost zone: 0.65 ≤ E² < 0.85. Transitional shapes — human silhouettes, vehicles, signage. Moderate simplification tolerance appropriate.
• Low cost zone: E² ≥ 0.85. Near-circular or near-hexagonal shapes — balls, appliances, regular objects. High simplification tolerance; minimal boundary information loss.
 
4. Synthetic Study — COCO Shape Class Distributions

4.1 Method
We modeled eight COCO-taxonomy shape classes using realistic E² distributions derived from known mask circularity statistics in the computer vision literature. Each class was sampled N=500 times from a Gaussian distribution parameterized by published mean and variance estimates for each category. Simplification error was modeled as ε = k·(1 − E²) + noise, where k=0.4 and noise ~ N(0, 0.03), consistent with empirical error-efficiency relationships in polygon approximation benchmarks.
Pearson correlation between E² and simplification error was computed per class. Triage zone assignment followed the classification defined in Section 3.2.
