Results confirm the diagnostic hypothesis across all eight classes. The correlation between E² and simplification error is consistently negative, ranging from r = −0.43 (Appliance, low-variance near-circular shapes) to r = −0.84 (Food, high-variance irregular shapes). The weaker correlation in low-cost zones reflects floor effects — when E² is already high, there is less variance in error to predict.
The triage classification cleanly separates the classes: person, animal, and food cluster in the high-cost zone; vehicles and furniture in the medium zone; balls and appliances in the low zone. This alignment with semantic category is a validation signal — the geometry is capturing real structural differences between object classes.
 
5. Discussion

5.1 Scope and Limitations
The diagnostic value of E² is strongest when the simplification target is a rectilinear or reduced-vertex representation — the setting directly grounded in the transform chain mathematics. Its utility as a predictor weakens when simplification preserves curve topology (e.g., spline fitting), because the circle-to-square distortion model no longer applies.
E² is a global scalar. It captures overall shape isotropy but is blind to local boundary complexity — a shape with a single deep notch may have the same E² as a smoothly rounded shape. Local complexity measures (fractal dimension, curvature variance) are complementary, not redundant. The appropriate use is as a fast O(1) pre-filter, not a replacement for full boundary analysis.
The claim that E² directly predicts physical system performance in domains such as stress concentration, antenna efficiency, or fluid dynamics is not supported by the mathematics presented here. E² may correlate with performance in isotropy-sensitive systems, but those claims require domain-specific derivation and empirical validation. The present paper makes no such claims.
5.2 Relationship to Known Results
The isoperimetric quotient 4πA/P² is a classical quantity appearing throughout differential geometry, image analysis, and computational biology under various names: circularity, shape factor, compactness index. The novelty of the present framing is not the quantity itself but the transform chain derivation that grounds it in a universal boundary conversion invariant, and the explicit application to pre-simplification triage as a precision budget allocation tool.
The connection to the Faber-Krahn inequality — which states that among all domains of fixed area, the disk minimizes the first Dirichlet eigenvalue — suggests a spectral geometry extension: E² as a proxy for eigenvalue penalty in non-circular confinement geometries. This is a plausible direction for future work but is not demonstrated here.
5.3 Implementation Note
For any segmentation mask with area A (pixel count) and perimeter P (boundary pixel count), E² is computed in a single line. No polygon fitting, no iterative optimization. The triage classification runs before any simplification algorithm and adds negligible overhead. Integration into existing OpenCV or scikit-image pipelines is straightforward.
E² = 4π·A / P²
 
6. Future Work

The research program implied by this framing has three tiers, ordered by current evidence level:
• Tier 1 — Immediately testable: Benchmark E²-guided triage against standard simplification algorithms on real COCO segmentation masks. Compare stopping criterion performance (error vs. vertex reduction) with and without E²-based tolerance setting. GIS polygon approximation is a parallel test domain.
• Tier 2 — Plausible with experiments: Diffusion and thermal spreading proxies (E² as shape compactness prior for heat spreader geometry comparison). Low-mode spectral penalty estimation (Faber-Krahn connection). Morphological prior weighting in segmentation networks.
• Tier 3 — Speculative, requires domain-specific derivation: Antenna coupling efficiency, hydraulic diameter correction, quantum confinement energy penalties. E² may serve as a morphological feature in these domains but direct predictive claims require independent derivation.
 
7. Conclusion

The equal-area transform chain from regular n-gon through circle to square produces a universal boundary conversion invariant R_CS = 2/√π that is independent of polygon side count. This invariant grounds the isoperimetric efficiency score E² as a principled geometric prior for shape simplification pipelines.
A synthetic study across eight COCO shape class distributions confirms strong negative correlation between E² and simplification error, validating the triage classification scheme. The diagnostic is O(1), parameter-free, and integrates trivially into existing pipelines.
The deeper claim — that π enters as the normalization constant for isotropic boundary efficiency in Euclidean 2-space, and that every shape's E² measures how much of that potential it expresses — is a productive interpretive frame even where it outruns current proof. The geometry is real. The invariant is exact. The applications are testable.
 
